---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="sych0net, Jeff Mills"
  description="A personal Astro site themed as a phosphor-amber BBS. Project logs, hardware galleries, ANSI art, and the vintage-computing aesthetic this site grew out of."
>
  <p class="project-back"><a href="/projects">&laquo; all projects</a></p>
  <h1 class="page-title">sych0net</h1>
  <p class="project-meta">
    <span class="project-year">2021, present</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span class="project-status">live</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span>personal site</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span>astro</span>
  </p>

  <p class="page-lede">
    <a href="https://sych0.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener">sych0.net</a>
    is my hobby site. It&rsquo;s a BBS-themed home for project logs, vintage
    computing builds, hardware galleries, and ANSI art, built in Astro,
    set in IBM Plex Mono, and rendered in amber-on-black like a CRT terminal
    that never went to sleep. It&rsquo;s also where the design language for
    <em>this</em> site came from.
  </p>

  <aside class="callout">
    <span class="callout-label">Where the phosphors never fade</span>
    <p>
      Sychonet exists because professional engineering work and weird old
      hardware deserve different rooms. The tagline,
      <em>&ldquo;where the phosphors never fade&rdquo;</em>, sums up
      the project: vintage computing as an active hobby, documented like a
      sysop&rsquo;s notebook.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">what&rsquo;s on it</h2>
  <ul class="proof-list">
    <li>
      <strong>Project logs</strong>, long-form documentation of
      restorations and builds: a GRiDCASE 1520 brought back from the dead, a
      Compaq Portable 486c restoration, an ESP32 Wi-Fi modem built to plug
      into a Compaq&rsquo;s enhanced options slot.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Hardware gallery</strong>, an inventory of the machines
      and peripherals on the bench, photographed and annotated.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Bulletin board</strong>, short sysop posts with
      BBS-board-name datacenter codes for vibes.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>ANSI art</strong>, classic scene art rendered with
      AnsiLove.js. A reminder that text-mode graphics had range.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Photo archive + message wall + system news</strong>, the
      mainstream BBS information architecture, applied unironically.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">why it&rsquo;s here</h2>
  <p>
    Sychonet matters to this portfolio for three reasons:
  </p>
  <ul class="proof-list">
    <li>
      <strong>It&rsquo;s the design language source.</strong> The
      phosphor-amber palette, the IBM Plex Mono typography, the 80-column
      shell, the dashed rules, the <code>&gt;</code> bullets, the dmesg-style
      log stream behind the CRT cursor on this site, all of it comes
      from sychonet&rsquo;s aesthetic vocabulary. This site is sychonet,
      dialed back from sysop to recruiter-safe.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>It&rsquo;s real published work outside the day job.</strong>
      Recruiters who skim &ldquo;hobby project&rdquo; and then click anyway
      land on a site that&rsquo;s genuinely shipped: keyboard-shortcut nav,
      lightbox image viewer, mobile-refusal &ldquo;phone wall&rdquo;
      easter-egg screen, custom Shiki theme, the works.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>It signals range.</strong> The same engineer architects
      regulated-finance design systems Monday through Friday and reverse-
      engineers a Compaq enhanced-options-slot on Saturday. The hardware work
      and the design-system work share a posture: take a thing seriously,
      learn how it&rsquo;s built, document it well.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">how it&rsquo;s built</h2>
  <p>
    Sychonet is intentionally simple infrastructure for a content-heavy site:
  </p>

  <dl class="stack-list">
    <dt>Framework</dt>
    <dd>Astro 5 (static-site generation, zero JS by default)</dd>
    <dt>Type</dt>
    <dd>Self-hosted IBM Plex Mono, no third-party fonts</dd>
    <dt>Content</dt>
    <dd>MDX + Astro content collections, photos optimized with Sharp</dd>
    <dt>Theme</dt>
    <dd>
      Custom Shiki TextMate theme (sychonet.json), the same one this
      site uses for code blocks
    </dd>
    <dt>Layout</dt>
    <dd>80-column shell, mobile refusal screen, lightbox image viewer</dd>
    <dt>Hosting</dt>
    <dd>GitHub Pages via Cloudflare Worker for asset rewriting</dd>
    <dt>Source</dt>
    <dd>
      <a href="https://github.com/k0bura/sychonet" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        github.com/k0bura/sychonet
      </a>
    </dd>
  </dl>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">design influences on this site</h2>
  <p>
    Direct lineage from sychonet to jeffmills.dev:
  </p>

  <ul class="proof-list">
    <li>
      Amber-phosphor palette (<code>#ffcc00</code> accent,
      <code>#665200</code> dim, <code>#88cc88</code> ok-green) and the dark
      <code>#0e0e0e</code> background.
    </li>
    <li>
      IBM Plex Mono everywhere, same font face, same weights,
      self-hosted from the same woff2 files.
    </li>
    <li>
      80-column shell, dashed-rule separators, <code>&gt;</code> bullets.
    </li>
    <li>
      The CRT cursor + dmesg log stream on this site is sychonet&rsquo;s
      aesthetic compressed into a single ambient effect.
    </li>
    <li>
      Custom Shiki theme for code blocks, amber keywords, green
      strings, blue functions, same palette across both sites.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Sychonet is the lab. This site is the production application.
  </p>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <p class="project-foot">
    Live: <a href="https://sycho.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener">sycho.net</a>
    &middot; Source: <a href="https://github.com/k0bura/sychonet" target="_blank" rel="noopener">github.com/k0bura/sychonet</a>
  </p>
</Base>

<style>
  .project-back {
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
    font-size: 0.85em;
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
  }

  .page-title {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    text-transform: lowercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    margin: 0.25rem 0 0.4rem;
  }

  .project-meta {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    font-size: 0.85em;
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.4rem;
    align-items: baseline;
  }

  .project-meta .project-year {
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
  }

  .project-meta .project-status {
    color: var(--jm-color-ok);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .meta-sep {
    color: var(--jm-color-border);
  }

  .page-lede {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
  }

  .section-title {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--jm-color-accent);
    text-transform: lowercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    margin: 2rem 0 0.5rem;
  }

  .stack-list {
    margin: 0.5rem 0 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: max-content 1fr;
    gap: 0.4rem 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .stack-list dt {
    color: var(--jm-color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.78em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    padding-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  .stack-list dd {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
    font-size: 0.95em;
  }

  @media (max-width: 540px) {
    .stack-list {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 0.2rem;
    }
    .stack-list dd {
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
  }

  .proof-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
    margin: 0.5rem 0 0;
  }

  .proof-list li {
    position: relative;
    margin: 0.6rem 0;
  }

  .proof-list li::before {
    content: ">";
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
    position: absolute;
    left: -1.25rem;
  }

  .proof-list strong {
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  code {
    font-family: var(--jm-font-mono);
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background: #1a1a1a;
    padding: 0.1em 0.35em;
  }

  .project-foot {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
    font-size: 0.9em;
  }
</style>
